Mixed Effect Linear Regression

Motivation

While a marginal model is suitable for examining average effects across the entire patient population, it may overlook potential variability and heterogeneity within subgroups or clusters (e.g., variations in treatment outcomes (remission) across different hospitals or physician practices).

There is strong evidence of clustering or hierarchical effects (e.g., certain physicians/hospital consistently achieve better mobility score), a mixed-effects model is more appropriate to account for such variability.

By incorporating random effects, mixed-effects models can account for the correlation among patients treated by the same physician or within the same hospital.

By capturing within-cluster correlations and variability, mixed-effects models can improve the precision of estimates and increase statistical power compared to marginal models that assume independence among observations.

Estimation

patient level predictor: age, cancer stage, length of stay

doctor level predictor: experience

random intercept: physician (DID)

Random Intercept Model

ri <- 
  lmer(mobility ~ Age  + Sex + LengthofStay + Experience  + (1 | DID), 
       data = cancer_1, 
       REML = FALSE)

Interpretation

Fixed Effect

  • The average score (or dependent variable value) when all other predictors (Age, Sex, Length of Stay, Experience) are zero is 7.53.

  • For each additional year of age, the score increases by approximately 0.025 (95% CI: -0.023, 0.027, p-value <0.001) when adjusted for sex, length of stay, physician experience, and random effect of physician.

  • Being female is associated with a decrease in the score by approximately 0.012 (95% CI: -0,04-0.013, p-value = 0.34) when adjusted for age, length of stay, physician experience, and random effect of physician.

  • Each additional day length of stay is associated with a decrease in the score by approximately 0.008 (95% CI: -0.02, -0.13,p-value = 0.25) when adjusted for age, gender, physician experience, and random effect of physician.

  • Additional years of experience is associated with a decrease in the score by approximately 0.155 (95% CI: -0.18- 0.005,p-value < 0.001) when adjusted for age, gender,length of stay, and random effect of physician.

    Random Effect

  • There is variability in the intercepts across different DID (treating doctors), with a standard deviation of 1.182, suggesting that different groups have different baseline scores.

  • After accounting for Age, Sex, Length of Stay, Experience effect, the proportion of unexplained variance due to difference between DID (Treating doctor) is 80.6%.

Random slope models

This will allow different slopes.

In our example, for random intercept model, we allowed for treating doctor effect on the mean score by allowing the intercept of the regression of mobility score on covariates to vary randomly across treating doctors. We assumed, however, that changes in covariates in mobility score are the same for all treating doctors, i.e.Â the slope of the regression line was assumed fixed across all treating doctors.

We will now extend the random intercept model fitted before to allow both the intercept and the slope to vary randomly across all treating doctors. Does the Working Experience (random slope) has variation across different DID (treating physician)?

rs <- lmer(mobility ~ Age + Sex + LengthofStay +  Experience + (1 + Experience | DID),

Interpretation

Fixed Effect

  • The average score (or dependent variable value) when all other predictors (Age, Sex, Length of Stay, Experience) are zero is 7.53.

  • For each additional year of age, the score increases by approximately 0.025 (95% CI: 0.023, 0.027, p-value <0.001) when adjusted for sex, length of stay, physician experience, and random effect of physician and length of stay.

  • Being female is associated with a decrease in the score by approximately 0.012 (95% CI: -0,04-0.013, p-value = 0.34) when adjusted for age, length of stay, physician experience, and random effect of physician and length of stay.

  • Each additional day length of stay is associated with a decrease in the score by approximately -0.008 (95% CI: -0.02, 0.05 ,p-value = 0.25) when adjusted for age, gender, physician experience, and random effect of physician and length of stay.

    Interpret the random slope and intercept together (random effect)

  • The working experience effect for DID is estimated as -0.1552161+ random_slope_experience. Between DID variance in these slopes estimated as 5.494e-08 (Variance of experience in random effect).

  • For average DID, we predict decrease in the mobility score by approximately -0.1552161for each additional years of experience. 95% coverage interval for the DID slopes is estimated asÂ - 0.1552161+/- 1.96 (Sqrt(5.494e-08)) which were between -0.154 and -0.156. Thus, assuming a normal distribution, we would expect the middle 95% of DID to have a slope between -0.154 and -0.156.

    -0.1552161 + (1.96 * sqrt(5.494e-08))
    [1] -0.1547567
    -0.1552161 - (1.96 * sqrt(5.494e-08))
    [1] -0.1556755

  • The correlation between the random intercept and the Experience effect is -1, indicating a perfect negative correlation. This means that as the intercept increases, the Experience effect (slope) decreases proportionally, and vice versa.

  • The standard deviation of the random slope for Experience across different groups is very close to zero (0.0002344), suggesting that there is almost no variability in the effect of Experience across the treating doctors.

Model Comparison

Lets compare between 2 models.

anova( ri, rs)
Data: cancer_1
Models:
ri: mobility ~ Age + Sex + LengthofStay + Experience + (1 | DID)
rs: mobility ~ Age + Sex + LengthofStay + Experience + (1 + Experience | DID)
   npar   AIC   BIC logLik deviance Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)
ri    7 16662 16711  -8324    16648                    
rs    9 16666 16729  -8324    16648 5e-04  2     0.9998

The AIC of model with random slope is almost similar to the model with random intercept. There are no significant improvement in model fit by adding random slope in model rs. Given the p-value 0.9998, we failed to reject the null hypothesis therefore simpler model (ri) is preferred. We conclude that, working experience effect had no random effect to treating doctor (DID).

Plot random effect

plot_model(ri, type = 're')

Plot shows the variability in the random intercepts for each treating doctor (DID) in the ri model. It indicates how much each DIDâs intercept differs from the overall mean intercept. The random effects vary significantly across treating doctors (DID), as shown by the spread of the points along the X-axis. This variability suggests that there are meaningful differences between the DID in determining the mobility score after accounting for Age, Sex, Length of Stay, and Experience.
